# Push Notification Standards

This document defines patterns for implementing push notifications on iOS and Android. All notification features must follow these standards.

---

## Token Management

### Registration Flow

- [ ] Request notification permission at contextually appropriate moment (not on first launch)
- [ ] Store device token on backend after successful registration
- [ ] Associate token with user ID after authentication
- [ ] Handle token refresh (iOS: token can change; Android: FCM token can rotate)
- [ ] Send token to backend on every app launch (idempotent upsert)
- [ ] Remove token from backend when user logs out or disables notifications

### Token Storage

| Location | Purpose |
|----------|---------|
| Backend (DB) | Map token to user; target pushes |
| Keychain (iOS) / EncryptedSharedPrefs (Android) | Persist for re-send on launch |
| Never in logs | Token is sensitive; do not log |

### Token Refresh Handling

```swift
// iOS: application(_:didRegisterForRemoteNotificationsWithDeviceToken:)
// Re-send to backend whenever called; Apple may call multiple times
func application(_ application: UIApplication,
                didRegisterForRemoteNotificationsWithDeviceToken deviceToken: Data) {
  let token = deviceToken.map { String(format: "%02.2hhx", $0) }.joined()
  backend.updateDeviceToken(token)
}
```

```kotlin
// Android: FirebaseMessaging.getInstance().token
// Listen for onNewToken; send to backend
FirebaseMessaging.getInstance().token.addOnCompleteListener { task ->
  if (task.isSuccessful) {
    backend.updateDeviceToken(task.result)
  }
}
```

