## Silent Push

### Use Case

Wake app for background sync, refresh content, or update without user-visible notification.

### iOS (Background Push)

- [ ] `content-available: 1` in aps
- [ ] No `alert`, `sound`, or `badge` (or minimal)
- [ ] App has limited time (~30s) to complete work
- [ ] Use BGAppRefreshTask or BGProcessingTask for longer work
- [ ] Do not rely on delivery; system may throttle

### Android (Data-Only)

- [ ] Omit `notification` key; include only `data`
- [ ] Handled by `FirebaseMessagingService.onMessageReceived`
- [ ] Works when app in background (service runs)
- [ ] Do not use for critical delivery; may be delayed or batched

### Best Practices

- [ ] Silent push is best-effort; do not assume delivery
- [ ] Use for non-critical updates (sync, prefetch)
- [ ] Respect user's battery and data; do not overuse
- [ ] Document rate limits and throttling expectations

---

## Handling and Routing

### On Tap

- [ ] Parse `deep_link` or equivalent from payload
- [ ] Route to correct in-app screen
- [ ] Pass context (e.g., order ID) for full load
- [ ] Handle when app was killed (cold start to destination)
- [ ] Clear badge when appropriate (iOS)

### When App in Foreground

- [ ] Decide: show in-app banner, in-app modal, or system notification
- [ ] Document behavior in product spec
- [ ] Do not duplicate (e.g., system + in-app) unless intentional
- [ ] Update UI if notification relates to visible content

### Foreground Handling (iOS)

```swift
func userNotificationCenter(_ center: UNUserNotificationCenter,
                            willPresent notification: UNNotification) -> UNNotificationPresentationOptions {
  // Return [] to suppress, or [.banner, .sound, .badge] to show
  return applicationState == .active ? [] : [.banner, .sound, .badge]
}
```

